            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <p>
                Deciding whether to repair or replace a stove can be a
                challenging decision. Here are some key factors to consider,
                using insights from repair services, the service range of your
                stove, and its performance over the past year:
              </p>

              <ol>
                <li>
                  <b>Age of the Stove</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair: If your stove is relatively new (typically less
                      than 10 years old), it might be more cost-effective to
                      repair it, as newer models tend to have parts that are
                      easier to find and replace.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replace: For stoves over 15 years old, replacement might
                      be a better option. Older stoves are less energy-efficient
                      and more prone to repeated breakdowns.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Cost of Repair</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair: Evaluate the cost of the repair. If the repair
                      service estimates that fixing the stove will cost less
                      than 50% of the price of a new stove, repairing might be
                      the more economical choice.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replace: If the repair cost is more than 50% of the price
                      of a new stove, it may be wiser to invest in a new one.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Service Range</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair: Consider the availability and range of services
                      offered by local repair professionals. If there are
                      reputable repair services nearby that specialize in your
                      stove's make and model, repairing could be convenient and
                      reliable.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replace: If you live in an area with limited repair
                      service options, or if the available services do not cover
                      your stove’s specific needs, replacing the stove might be
                      the more practical solution.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Frequency of Issues Over the Past Year</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair: If your stove has only had occasional minor issues
                      over the past year, it may just need a one-time fix to
                      keep it running smoothly.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replace: If you’ve had to call for repairs multiple times
                      in the past year, it could indicate that the stove is
                      nearing the end of its lifespan and it might be time to
                      consider a replacement.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Energy Efficiency</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair: If your stove is relatively energy-efficient and
                      meets current standards, repairing it can help maintain
                      those benefits.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replace: Newer stoves generally offer improved energy
                      efficiency. If your current stove is consuming a lot of
                      energy, replacing it could save you money on utility bills
                      in the long run.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Availability of Parts</b>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Repair: If parts for your stove are readily available and
                      affordable, repairing can be a straightforward process.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Replace: If parts are obsolete or extremely expensive,
                      replacing the stove might be more sensible.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>

